  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: The Double Coat in the Tropics" imageAlt="Golden Retriever having its double coat brushed with an undercoat rake" imageSrc={imgScene4} imagePosition="left">
      <p>The golden coat is a commitment stated in kilograms per year. Brush 3 to 4 times a week with a proper undercoat rake, daily during the twice-yearly coat blows, and accept that golden hair becomes a household condiment. Baths monthly or after sea swims, with thorough drying, a damp undercoat in tropical humidity is how hot spots start.</p>
      <p>And the rule we repeat on every double-coated page, because Singapore groomers still get asked weekly: never shave a Golden. The coat insulates against heat as well as cold, protects the skin from sun, and shaving wrecks how it grows back. Brush it, don't shave it.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Golden Health: What We Check and What to Watch" imageAlt="Golden Retriever puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene5} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Golden goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The Golden health conversation has two parts, and honest pages have both. The manageable part: hip and elbow dysplasia run in large breeds, so puppyhood is joint-protective by design, controlled growth feeding, no stair marathons, no forced running before maturity, and a lean weight for life. The part that deserves plain words: Goldens carry higher cancer rates than most breeds, typically in later life, and the practical response is early, regular senior checks from around age seven, when catching things early genuinely changes outcomes.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple but breed-specific: your puppy comes with the large-breed food it is already eating, portioned for controlled growth, and any change should be gradual over a week. See the <a href="/learn/puppy-health" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Golden's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Golden Retriever puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene6} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Golden explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person, including the large-breed feeding plan. Learn more about <a href="/delivery" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and joint-safe. A fixed feeding routine with measured portions, the toilet pads where we placed them, and play that stays on the floor, no leaping, no stairs, while those big-breed joints are growing.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks, and for a dog headed to thirty kilograms this is the non-negotiable week: book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer now, because manners installed at five kilos are a gift at thirty. See <a href="/free-training" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

